{{Politics of Guam}} A '''referendum on a new constitution''' was held in [[Guam]] on 8 August 1987.<ref>[http://www.sudd.ch/list.php?lang=en&area=guam&topic=&first=&last=&sense=desc] Direct Democracy {{de icon}}</ref> Instead of passing the whole constitution as a unit, voters chose to approve each chapter of the document individually. With a low turnout of 39%, all chapters were approved<ref>http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=gu021987</ref> except for Chapter I on relations with the [[United States]]<ref>http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=gu011987</ref> and Chapter VII on [[Chamorro people|Chamorro]] relations and immigration.<ref>http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=gu071987</ref> Modified versions of these rejected chapters would be accepted in a [[Guamanian constitutional referendum, November 1987|referendum later the same year]].
==November== A '''referendum on chapters of a constitution''' was held in [[Guam]] on 7 November 1987.<ref>[http://www.sudd.ch/list.php?lang=en&area=guam&topic=&first=&last=&sense=desc] Direct Democracy {{de icon}}</ref> Chapter I (on relations with the United States)<ref>http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=gu131987</ref> and Chapter VII (on [[Chamorro people|Chamorro]] relations and immigration)<ref>http://www.sudd.ch/event.php?lang=en&id=gu141987</ref> had been rejected in a [[Guamanian constitutional referendum, August 1987|referendum in August]], and the Constitutional Commission resubmitted modified versions. Both modified versions passed on the back of a much higher turnout of 58%.
